.\" cligPart DESCRIPTION
.SH DESCRIPTION
prepfold folds one pulsar candidate -- raw radio data
(SIGPROC filterbank or PSRFITS), an already-dedispersed time series,
or an event/photon list -- and, unless told not to
.RB ( -nosearch
and friends), refines the fold by searching a small volume around the
input period/frequency, its derivative(s), and (for raw data) DM,
writing a
.I .pfd
file plus a postscript summary plot.  For folding many candidates in
one pass over the raw data (e.g. a batch of
.BR accelsearch (1)
candidates), see
.BR prepfold_multi (1)
instead.
.PP
The folding parameters can come from several sources: explicit
.BR -p / -pd / -pdd
or
.BR -f / -fd / -fdd ;
.B -accelcand
plus
.B -accelfile
to fold a specific candidate straight out of an
.BR accelsearch (1)
.I .cand
file (use
.B -pfact
or
.B -ffact
if the candidate looks like a harmonic); a
.BR -par
file or
.B -psr
name looked up against the ATNF pulsar database; or
.BR -timing ,
which folds with TEMPO2-generated polycos (no searching), sets the DM
and profile-bin count automatically, and produces a
.I .pfd
suitable for TOA generation with
.IR get_TOAs.py .
.PP
.B -fine
narrows the searched p/pd/pdd/DM volume (good for a well-constrained,
faint candidate);
.B -coarse
widens it (good when the ephemeris is uncertain);
.B -slow
combines
.B -fine
with more profile bins for long-period pulsars.
For raw data,
.B -nsub
(typically 64-128) sets the frequency resolution used for the DM
search and RFI rejection, and
.B -mask
/
.B -ignorechan
apply an
.BR rfifind (1)
mask or explicit channel list.  If interference inflates the
off-pulse chi^2 after the fact, see
.BR show_pfd (1)
.BR -fixchi .
.PP
Example: a quick look at an
.BR accelsearch (1)
candidate straight from the barycentered time series it was found
in, to see if it looks pulsar-like before investing in a full raw-data
fold:
.RS
.nf
prepfold -accelcand 2 -accelfile mypulsar_DM238.30_ACCEL_20.cand mypulsar_DM238.30.dat
.fi
.RE
.PP
Example: the same candidate, but folded from the raw data with a
range of trial DMs around its search DM, using
.B -dm
and
.B -nsub
64 subbands -- much slower, but shows whether there's a genuine
signal-to-noise peak in DM (a good sign it's a real pulsar rather
than RFI or a DM=0 artifact):
.RS
.nf
prepfold -dm 238.30 -nsub 64 -accelcand 2 -accelfile mypulsar_DM238.30_ACCEL_20.cand mypulsar.fits
.fi
.RE
.PP
Example: fold raw data at an already-known period and period
derivative and DM, applying an
.BR rfifind (1)
mask:
.RS
.nf
prepfold -p 8.66430621957513e-3 -pd -5.01154755640048e-11 -dm 238.30 -mask mypulsar_rfifind.mask mypulsar.fits
.fi
.RE
.PP
Example: a timing-quality fold of raw data using a par file, with 64
subbands and a few known-bad channels excluded outright:
.RS
.nf
prepfold -timing mypulsar.par -nsub 64 -ignorechan 0:3 mypulsar.fits
.fi
.RE

